### Start Node.js Application with ESM Loader

Source: https://github.com/newrelic/node-newrelic/blob/main/README.md

Starts a Node.js application using the `--import` flag to load the New Relic ESM loader, enabling the agent to instrument ES Modules correctly. This is essential for applications written with `import` and `export` statements.

```sh
$ node --import newrelic/esm-loader.mjs -r newrelic your-program.js
```

--------------------------------

### Setup New Relic for Next.js with NODE_OPTIONS

Source: https://github.com/newrelic/node-newrelic/blob/main/README.md

Starts a Next.js application with the New Relic agent automatically loaded via the NODE_OPTIONS environment variable. This is the recommended method for instrumenting Next.js applications.

```bash
NODE_OPTIONS='-r newrelic' next start
```

--------------------------------

### Require New Relic Agent at Program Start

Source: https://github.com/newrelic/node-newrelic/blob/main/README.md

Loads the New Relic agent module at the very beginning of your Node.js program. This ensures that all subsequent modules and operations are instrumented for performance monitoring.

```javascript
const newrelic = require('newrelic')

/* ... the rest of your program ... */
```

--------------------------------

### Run Node.js Application with New Relic Agent

Source: https://github.com/newrelic/node-newrelic/blob/main/README.md

Executes your Node.js program with the 'newrelic' module pre-loaded using the '-r' or '--require' flag. This is a common method for starting an instrumented Node.js application.

```bash
node -r newrelic your-program.js
```

